  "prompt": "What function do we use in Java in place of cin>> in C++?",
  "response": "In Java, the functionality equivalent to `cin >>` in C++ for reading input from the user can be achieved using the `Scanner` class. The `Scanner` class provides methods for reading different types of input tokens, such as strings and primitive types like int, double, etc.\n\nHere\u2019s an example of reading a string and an integer input using `Scanner`:\n\n```java\nimport java.util.Scanner;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);\n\n        // Read a string input\n        System.out.print(\"Enter a string: \");\n        String inputString = scanner.nextLine();\n\n        // Read an integer input\n        System.out.print(\"Enter an integer: \");\n        int inputInt = scanner.nextInt();\n\n        System.out.println(\"You entered the string: \" + inputString);\n        System.out.println(\"You entered the integer: \" + inputInt);\n\n        scanner.close();\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this example:\n- `scanner.nextLine()` is used to read a line of text from the user.\n- `scanner.nextInt()` is used to read an integer.\n\nMake sure to import the `java.util.Scanner` package when using the `Scanner` class.",
